H.B. 876
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
Apr 9, 2025
SESSION 2025
HOUSE PRINCIPAL CLERK
H D
HOUSE BILL DRH40476-MQ-93
Short Title: Development Application Review Time Lines. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Gillespie.
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO REQUIRE REVIEW OF CERTAIN DEVELOPMENT APPROVALS AND
3 BUILDING INSPECTIONS BY LOCAL GOVERNMENTS WITHIN TWO BUSINESS
4 DAYS OF REQUEST.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1. Article 4 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended by
7 adding a new section to read:
8 "§ 160D-402.1. Administrative review of applications for development approvals.
9 (a) Within two business days of a local government's receipt of an application for
10 development approval, the local government shall complete an administrative review of the
11 application and any supporting documents and make an administrative decision that does one of
12 the following:
13 (1) Notifies the developer in writing that the application is complete and no
14 further information is required for the local government to make a
15 development approval determination.
16 (2) Notifies the developer in writing that the application is deficient and provides
17 the developer with a deficiency list, in writing, that identifies all of the
18 following:
19 a. Each deficiency.
20 b. The specific law, ordinance, policy, or procedure used as the basis for
21 each deficiency.
22 c. A description of the action the local government would deem
23 corrective for each deficiency identified.
24 (b) The notice under subdivision (2) of subsection (a) of this section may include local
25 government recommendations pertaining to the development project but any recommendations
26 must be clearly designated as recommended or advisory only and shall not be required as a
27 condition for a development approval determination.
28 (c) Upon a developer's receipt of a notice of a deficient application and a deficiency list
29 under subdivision (2) of subsection (a) of this section, the developer may do any of the following:
30 (1) Correct the deficient application and resubmit a corrected application to the
31 local government.
32 (2) Submit a written explanation for each deficiency and request another
33 administrative review under this section that shall be completed by the local
34 government within two business days and takes into consideration the written
35 explanation.
36 (3) Appeal the administrative decision as provided in G.S. 160D-405.
*DRH40476-MQ-93*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (d) Within two business days of a local government's receipt of a corrected application
2 under subdivision (1) of subsection (c) of this section, the local government shall notify the
3 developer in writing whether the application (i) is complete and no further information is required
4 for the local government to make a development approval determination or (ii) does not correct
5 all of the deficiencies identified in accordance with subdivision (2) of subsection (a) of this
6 section. If the developer amended or altered the application with respect to matters that are
7 unrelated to the deficiencies identified in accordance with subdivision (2) of subsection (a) of
8 this section, the local government shall consider the corrected application a new application to
9 be processed in accordance with subsection (a) of this section.
10 (e) A local government may utilize and contract with the Department of Insurance and
11 its marketplace pool of qualified Code-enforcement officials or contract with a licensed
12 professional engineer or licensed architect certified under G.S. 143-151.13(f) to perform
13 independent third-party plan reviews under this section, provided that the review time does not
14 exceed time frames prescribed by this section.
15 (f) If the local government does not issue applicable application decisions or determines
16 it is unable to complete application reviews within the time frames prescribed by this section, the
17 permit applicant may elect to utilize and contract with the Department of Insurance and its
18 marketplace pool of qualified Code-enforcement officials or elect to contract with a licensed
19 professional engineer or licensed architect certified under G.S. 143-151.13(f) to perform
20 independent third-party plan reviews and certify submitted plans as required by subsection (g) of
21 this section. Upon acceptance of a completed plan review with certification required by
22 subsection (g) of this section, the local government shall issue applicable permits for the project
23 within two business days and will refund or waive all applicable plan review and permit fees for
24 the project upon issuance of the applicable permits.
25 (g) An applicant that elects a third-party review under subsection (f) of this section shall
26 provide the local government with a written certification signed by the plan reviewer that plans
27 comply with applicable North Carolina State Building Codes and all other applicable State and
28 local laws. The certification shall be made on a form created by the local government.
29 (h) Conflicts of Interest. – Notwithstanding G.S. 160D-1108, a third-party plan reviewer
30 shall avoid conflicts of interest in conducting independent third-party plan reviews under this
31 section. Conflicts of interest include a plan reviewer having any financial interest in, or being
32 employed, other than as a plan reviewer under this section, by a business that has a financial
33 interest in, the furnishing of labor, material, or appliances for the construction, alteration, or
34 maintenance of, or any involvement in the making of plans or specifications for, the project
35 subject to plan review.
36 (i) This section shall not apply to permit applications submitted pursuant to
37 G.S. 160D-1110.1."
38 SECTION 2. G.S. 160D-1110(b) reads as rewritten:
39 "(b) A building permit shall be in writing and shall contain a provision that the work done
40 shall comply with the North Carolina State Building Code and all other applicable State and local
41 laws. Nothing in this section requires a local government to review and approve residential
42 building plans submitted to the local government pursuant to the North Carolina Residential
43 Code, so long as the local government may review and approve the residential building plans as
44 it deems necessary. If a local government chooses to review residential building plans for any
45 structures subject to regulation under the North Carolina Residential Code, all initial reviews for
46 the building permit shall be performed within 15 two business days of submission of the plans.
47 plans, in accordance with G.S. 160D-402.1. A local government shall not require residential
48 building plans for one- and two-family dwellings to be sealed by a licensed engineer or licensed
49 architect unless required by the North Carolina State Building Code. No building permits shall
50 be issued unless the plans and specifications are identified by the name and address of their
51 author. If the General Statutes require that plans for certain types of work be prepared only by a
Page 2 DRH40476-MQ-93

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 licensed architect or licensed engineer, no building permit shall be issued unless the plans and
2 specifications bear the North Carolina seal of a licensed architect or of a licensed engineer. When
3 any provision of the General Statutes or of any ordinance or development or zoning regulation
4 requires that work be done by a licensed specialty contractor of any kind, no building permit for
5 the work shall be issued unless the work is to be performed by a licensed contractor."
6 SECTION 3. G.S. 160D-1104 reads as rewritten:
7 "§ 160D-1104. Duties and responsibilities.
8 (a) The duties and responsibilities of an inspection department and of the inspectors in it
9 are to enforce within their planning and development regulation jurisdiction State and local laws
10 relating to the following:
11 (1) The construction of buildings and other structures.
12 (2) The installation of such facilities as plumbing systems, electrical systems,
13 heating systems, refrigeration systems, and air-conditioning systems.
14 (3) The maintenance of buildings and other structures in a safe, sanitary, and
15 healthful condition.
16 (4) Other matters that may be specified by the governing board.
17 (b) The duties and responsibilities set forth in subsection (a) of this section include the
18 receipt of applications for permits and the issuance or denial of permits, the making of any
19 necessary inspections in a timely manner, not to exceed two business days from the first request
20 for an inspection, the issuance or denial of certificates of compliance, the issuance of orders to
21 correct violations, the bringing of judicial actions against actual or threatened violations, the
22 keeping of adequate records, and any other actions that may be required in order adequately to
23 enforce those laws. If an inspection cannot be completed within two business days from the first
24 request for inspection, the inspection department shall notify the permit holder. The governing
25 board has the authority to enact reasonable and appropriate provisions governing the enforcement
26 of those laws.
27 …."
28 SECTION 4. G.S. 143-151.8(a)(3) reads as rewritten:
29 "(3) Code enforcement. – The examination and approval of plans and
30 specifications, the inspection of the manner of construction, workmanship,
31 and materials for construction of buildings and structures and their
32 components, or the enforcement of fire code regulations by any of the
33 following, to assure compliance with the State Building Code and related local
34 building rules:
35 a. An employee of the State or local government, except an employee of
36 the State Department of Labor engaged in the administration and
37 enforcement of sections of the Code that pertain to boilers and
38 elevators.
39 b. An employee of a federally recognized Indian Tribe employed to
40 perform inspections on tribal lands.
41 c. An individual contracting with the State, a local government, or a
42 federally recognized Indian Tribe to perform inspections on tribal
43 lands.
44 d. An individual who is employed by a company contracting with a
45 county or a city to conduct inspections.
46 e. A person who is contracting with a local government to perform
47 third-party plan reviews under G.S. 160D-402.1(e).
48 f. A person who is contracting with a permit applicant to perform
49 third-party plan reviews under G.S. 160D-402.1(f)."
50 SECTION 5. G.S. 143-151.12(9) reads as rewritten:
